  1. Is this an observational study or an experiment? The original research question posed in the paper is whether beauty leads directly to the differences in course evaluations. Given the study design, is it possible to answer this question as it is phrased? If not, rephrase the question.

This is an observational study making it difficult to make causal claims. The more appropriate research question would be whether there is an association between beauty and course evaluation score.

  1. Describe the distribution of score. Is the distribution skewed? What does that tell you about how students rate courses? Is this what you expected to see? Why, or why not?
qplot(x = score, data = evals, binwidth = 0.1, color = I("white"))

summary(evals$score)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   2.300   3.800   4.300   4.175   4.600   5.000

The distribution of score takes a range between about 2.5 and 5, has a median score of 4.3 and an IQR of just less than 1. The shape is skewed to the left, which is what I expected. Students tend to be fairly generous, rating their professors either 4s or 5s, though occasionally there will be a professor that is quite unpopular. Even so, I am surprised at how high the minimum actually was: 2.3.

The teaching faculty was an even split and the tenure track faculty show an over-representation of women (around two thirds).

The initial scatterplot has lots of over-plotting - one dot representing many observations. Jittering fixes this by moving each of those stacks of dots just a bit so that theyre no longer on top of one another.

  1. Lets see if the apparent trend in the plot is something more than natural variation. Fit a linear model called m_bty to predict average professor score by average beauty rating. Write out the equation for the linear model and interpret the slope. Is average beauty score a statistically significant predictor? Does it appear to be a practically significant predictor?

\[ \hat{y} = 3.88 + 0.06 \times bty\_avg \]

It is a statistically significant predictor based on the small \(p\)-value. One would hope that beauty was not, in practice, a predictor of score though.

  1. Use residual plots to evaluate whether the conditions of least squares regression are reasonable. Provide plots and comments for each one (see the Simple Regression Lab for a reminder of how to make these).
qplot(x = .fitted, y = .stdresid, data = m_bty) + geom_jitter()

qplot(sample = .stdresid, data = m_bty) + geom_abline()

The linearity assumption seems reasonable given that our residual plot is fairly structure-less and the residuals are centered at zero across the range of fitted values. The constant variance assumption is also reasonable as the variance in the residuals looks to be constant across the range of fitted values. The more problematic assumption is that of normally distributed errors. The qq plot shows that we have a left skewed distribution (long left tail, short right tail). Finally, regarding the assumption of independent errors, there is no sign in the residuals of serial correlation. In terms of how the data was collected, if each row in our data set corresponds to a unique professor, its unlikely that there are over 4000 professors at this university, so we have reason to think that our sample constitutes more than 10% of the population and therefore that our errors may not be independent of one another.

  1. \(P\)-values and parameter estimates should only be trusted if the conditions for the regression are reasonable. Verify that the conditions for this model are reasonable using diagnostic plots.
qplot(x = .fitted, y = .stdresid, data = m_bty_gen) + geom_jitter()

qplot(sample = .stdresid, data = m_bty_gen) + geom_abline()

The residual plot and the qq plot look very similar to that for the first model and thus the conclusions are the same: the normality assumption in the errors seems unrealistic and the independent errors assumption is questionable. Because of this, we expect that our \(p\)-values and parameter estimates may be off.

  1. Is bty_avg still a significant predictor of score? Has the addition of gender to the model changed the parameter estimate for bty_avg?

Yes, bty_avg is still significant. The addition of gender has changed the estimate only slightly, from 0.066 to 0.074.

  1. What is the equation of the line corresponding to males? (Hint: For males, the parameter estimate is multiplied by 1.) For two professors who received the same beauty rating, which gender tends to have the higher course evaluation score?

\[ \hat{y} = (3.75 + 0.1724) + 0.074 \times bty\_avg \] \[ \hat{y} = 3.92 + 0.074 \times bty\_avg \]

For two professors of the same beauty rating, our model predicts that the male professor will have a score that is 0.1723 points higher.

We will start with a full model that predicts professor score based on rank, ethnicity, gender, language of the university where they got their degree, age, proportion of students that filled out evaluations, class size, course level, number of professors, number of credits, average beauty rating, outfit, and picture color.

  1. Which variable would you expect to have the highest \(p\)-value in this model? Why? Hint: Think about which variable would you expect to not have any association with the professor score.

Id expect pic_color to have the highest \(p\)-value in the model since it seems like it should be independent of score.

  1. Verify that the conditions for this model are reasonable using diagnostic plots.
qplot(x = .fitted, y = .stdresid, data = m_final) + geom_jitter()

qplot(sample = .stdresid, data = m_final) + geom_abline(col = "green")

This model is violating assumptions left and right. The linear trend looks like the only sensible assumption give that the residuals are centered at zero across the range of the fitted values. The funnel-shaped pattern, however, indicates some decreasing variance. Additionally, our residuals are still left-skewed and we have the same reservations about independence.

  1. Based on your final model, describe the characteristics of a professor and course at University of Texas at Austin that would be associated with a high evaluation score.

A high evaluation score would be associated with a professor who is male, not a minority, a native English speaker, young, rated to have high beauty using a black-and-white photo, has a high eval completion rate, and is teaching a one credit course.

  1. The original paper describes how these data were gathered by taking a sample of professors from the University of Texas at Austin and including all courses that they have taught. Considering that each row represents a course, could this new information have an impact on any of the conditions of linear regression?

This makes the assumption of independent errors even less tenable as wed expect that courses taught by the same professor will have similar scores.

  1. Would you be comfortable generalizing your conclusions to apply to professors generally (at any university)? Why or why not?

We would be comfortable generalizing our conclusions to the broader population of all professors if our sample is representative of that population (thats be once we have a valid model). There is good reason to think that the dynamics at play in a large research university like UT Austin will be quite different than those at a small liberals arts college like, say, Reed. Therefore wed want to restrict our generalization to similar large universities.
